---
import DocsLayout from '../../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import Callout from '../../../../components/Callout.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../../../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import StepList from '../../../../components/StepList.astro';
import Checklist from '../../../../components/Checklist.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Deployment" description="Blue/green deployment — deploy new versions with zero downtime by switching ALB target groups.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">Deployment</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Blue/green deployment is the star of this step. Instead of taking the application down, deploying the new version, and bringing it back up — you deploy the new version alongside the old one, verify it works, and switch traffic. If something goes wrong, you switch back. Zero downtime.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Blue/green deployment step by step</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">This is the deployment pipeline, automated through GitHub Actions:</p>

  <StepList steps={[
    { title: "Create new target group (green)", content: "Terraform creates a new ALB target group for the new version." },
    { title: "Launch new EC2 instance", content: "Deploy the new application version to a fresh EC2 instance. Register it with the green target group." },
    { title: "Run database migrations", content: "Apply any pending Alembic migrations. The migration must be backward-compatible — the old version (blue) is still running against the same database." },
    { title: "Health checks", content: "ALB health checks verify the new instance is healthy. The health endpoint returns 200, application responds to requests, database is connected." },
    { title: "Switch ALB listener", content: "Update the ALB listener to forward traffic to the green target group. New requests go to the new version." },
    { title: "Drain connections from blue", content: "The old instance finishes processing in-flight requests. No new requests are routed to it. The ALB deregistration delay handles this (default: 300 seconds)." },
    { title: "Verify and terminate blue", content: "After drain period, verify the new version is stable. Terminate the old EC2 instance. Green is now the live environment." },
  ]} />

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Rollback is a switch, not a rebuild.</strong> If the green instance fails health checks, the ALB never switches — blue stays live, green is terminated, no impact. If green passes health checks but has a bug discovered after switching, you re-register the blue instance (if still running) or redeploy the previous version. The key: keep the blue instance alive for a buffer period after switching.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Backward-compatible migrations</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">The hardest part of blue/green deployment. During the switch, the old version (blue) and new version (green) briefly run against the same database. Migrations must not break the old version.</p>

  <div class="space-y-4 mb-8">
    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mb-2">Safe migration patterns</h3>
      <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2">
        <li><strong class="text-text">Add a column:</strong> Safe. The old version ignores the new column.</li>
        <li><strong class="text-text">Add a table:</strong> Safe. The old version doesn't know about it.</li>
        <li><strong class="text-text">Add an index:</strong> Safe but may lock the table briefly on large datasets.</li>
        <li><strong class="text-text">Make a column nullable:</strong> Safe. Existing data and queries still work.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-base font-semibold mb-2">Unsafe migration patterns</h3>
      <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2">
        <li><strong class="text-text">Rename a column:</strong> Breaks the old version — its queries reference the old name.</li>
        <li><strong class="text-text">Remove a column:</strong> Breaks the old version — its queries reference the deleted column.</li>
        <li><strong class="text-text">Change a column type:</strong> May break the old version depending on implicit casts.</li>
        <li><strong class="text-text">Add a NOT NULL constraint without default:</strong> Breaks inserts from the old version that don't include the column.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <Callout variant="warning">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Unsafe migrations require a two-phase approach.</strong> To rename a column: Phase 1 — add the new column (safe), deploy code that writes to both columns. Phase 2 — after all instances use the new column, drop the old one. This is more complex but ensures zero-downtime compatibility.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">GitHub Actions pipeline</h2>
  <CodeBlock copy>{`Set up the GitHub Actions deployment pipeline:

1. On push to develop: deploy to staging (standard deploy, not blue/green — staging doesn't need zero downtime)
2. On push to main: blue/green deploy to production
   - Terraform creates new target group and EC2 instance
   - Deploy application to new instance
   - Run Alembic migrations
   - Wait for ALB health checks to pass
   - Switch ALB listener to new target group
   - Wait for connection draining
   - Terminate old instance

Include rollback step: if health checks fail after 5 minutes, terminate the new instance and keep the old one live.`}</CodeBlock>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Deployment verification</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">After a blue/green deploy, verify:</p>
  <Checklist items={[
    "The application responds on the production URL (no errors)",
    "Login works for all three user types",
    "Appointment booking works across all three locations",
    "Clinical notes can be written and viewed",
    "Database schema is correct (migration applied successfully)",
    "ALB health checks show the new target group as healthy",
    "Old target group is draining or terminated",
    "Grafana dashboards show normal metrics (no error spikes)",
  ]} />

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Zero-downtime verification</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">The whole point of blue/green is zero downtime. Prove it works:</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">During a deployment, run a simple load test — continuous requests to the health endpoint or a read endpoint. After deployment completes, check: did any requests fail? If the answer is zero failures, the blue/green deployment works. If requests failed during the switch, the ALB listener update or connection draining needs tuning.</p>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>This is a real production technique.</strong> Teams running blue/green in production monitor error rates during every deploy. A spike in errors during the switch means something is misconfigured — health check timing, drain period, or migration compatibility. The deployment itself is a thing you observe and verify, not just fire and forget.</p>
  </Callout>

  <details class="my-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary class="px-6 py-4 bg-bg-muted cursor-pointer font-semibold text-sm">The landscape: zero-downtime deployment patterns</summary>
    <div class="px-6 py-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4">Blue/green is one approach to zero-downtime deployment. Here's the broader landscape.</p>
      <div class="space-y-3">
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Blue/green with ALB</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">What we use. Two target groups, one active. Instant switch. Best for single-instance or small-fleet deployments. Simple mental model.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Rolling deployment (ECS/Kubernetes)</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Replace containers one at a time in a managed cluster. The orchestrator handles health checks and traffic routing. Standard for container-based deployments. Slower but uses fewer resources than blue/green.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Canary with weighted routing</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Route 5% of traffic to the new version, monitor error rates, gradually increase to 100%. AWS ALB supports weighted target groups. Safest for high-traffic systems where even blue/green feels risky.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Immutable infrastructure</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Never update a running instance. Create a new AMI (machine image) with the new version, launch a new instance from it, switch traffic. The old instance is destroyed, not updated. Prevents configuration drift.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Expand/contract migrations</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">The database side of zero-downtime. Phase 1 (expand): add the new column, keep the old one, deploy code that writes to both. Phase 2 (contract): remove the old column after all instances use the new one. Two migrations, two deployments, zero downtime.</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-4">Blue/green with ALB is the right complexity level for Coastal Physio. The concepts scale — canary, rolling, and immutable infrastructure are the same ideas applied to larger systems. The migration timing challenge (expand/contract) is universal across all zero-downtime strategies.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <div class="mt-8 p-6 bg-primary-bg rounded-lg border border-primary/20 text-center">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-2">Next: UAT</h2>
    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Deployed and verified. Time to show Megan.</p>
    <a
      href="/web-dev/projects/7/uat"
      class="inline-block bg-primary hover:bg-primary-dark text-white font-semibold py-3 px-6 rounded-md transition-colors min-h-[44px]"
    >
      UAT →
    </a>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
